Mylu Praveen

========================================================

Introduction:

This tidy data set contains 4,898 white wines with 11 variables on quantifying the chemical properties of each wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

Description of Attributes from Data:

  1. fixed acidity: most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily).

  2. volatile acidity: The amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste.

  3. citric acid: found in small quantities, citric acid can add freshness and flavor to wines.

  4. residual sugar: the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, its rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet.

  5. chlorides: the amount of salt in the wine.

  6. free sulfur dioxide: the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine.

  7. total sulfur dioxide: amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine.

  8. density: the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content.

  9. pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale.

  10. sulphates: a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant.

  11. alcohol: the percent alcohol content of the wine

    Output variable (based on sensory data):

  12. quality (score between 0 and 10).

New Variables:

  1. Volatile.type: represents taste where low level tends to have a good taste.

  2. citric.type: represents amount of flavour in wine.

  3. quality.type: represents quality on a basis of low, medium and high.

  4. total.acidity: represents total amount of acidity in wine. (total.acidity = fixed.acidity + volatile.acidity)

Univariate Plots Section

  • fixed.acidity has an normal distribution with a mean of 6.855. It has a median of value 6.8 and there are very few outliers after the fixed.acidity value of 10 in this plot . The maximum count for fixed.acidity is nearly 310. fixed.acidity has an interval range of {3.80, 14.2}.

  • volatile.acidity is a positive skew distribution with a mean of 0.08. It has a median of a value 0.26 and there are no outliers in this plot. The maximum count for volatile.acidity is almost 2000. volatile.acidity has an interval range of {0.08, 1.10}.

  • citric.acid is a normal distribution with a mean of 0.3342. It has a median of a value 0.32 and there are no outliers in this plot. The maximum count for volatile.acidity is almost 2250. citric.acid has an interval range of {0, 1.66}.

  • residual.sugar is a positive skew distribution with a mean of 6.391. It has a median of a value 5.2 and there are few outliers in this plot occuring after the residual.sugar value of 20. The maximum count for residual.sugar is almost 185. residual.sugar has an interval range of {0.60, 65.8}.

  • chlorides is a positive skew distribution with a mean of 0.045. It has a median of a value 0.043 and there are no outliers in this plot. The maximum count for chlorides is almost 1100. chlorides has an interval range of {0.009, 0.346}.

  • total.sulfur.dioxide is a bimodal distribution with a mean of 138.4. It has a median of a value 134 and there are no outliers in this plot. The maximum count for total.sulfur.dioxide is nearly 50. total.sulfur.dioxide has an interval range of {9, 440}.

  • pH is a binomial distribution with a mean of 3.188. It has a median of a value 3.18 and there are no outliers in this plot. The maximum count for pH is almost 1300. pH has an interval range of {2.72, 3.82}.

  • sulphates is a binomial distribution with a mean of 0.4898. It has a median of a value 0.47 and there are no outliers in this plot. The maximum count for sulphates is almost 1700. sulphates has an interval range of {0.22, 1.08}.

  • alcohol is a positive skew distribution with a mean of 10.51. It has a median of a value 10.4 and there is an single outlier near to 14 in this plot. The maximum count for alcohol is almost 235. alcohol has an interval range of {8, 14.2}.

  • quality is a bimodal distribution with a mean of 5.878. quality is an ordered categorical variableIt has a median of a value 6 and there are no outliers in this plot. The maximum count for volatile.acidity is almost 2250. quality has an interval range of {0.08, 1.10}.

New variables Plots Section

  • White wine produces more amount of low volatile.type which says it consists of more amount of good taste. low volatile.type has a count of 4742, middle volatile.type of 90 and high volatile.type of 66.

  • White wine consists of less amount of flavour in wine. less citric.type has a count of 4584, medium citric.type of 312 and more citric.type of 2.

  • White wine produces a better quality wine. normal quality.type has a count of 20, better quality.type of 3818 and good quality.type of 1060.

  • total amount of acidity is an binomial distribution with a mean of 7.133. It has a median of a value 7.07 and there are no outliers in this plot. The maximum count for total.acidity is almost 900. total.acidity has an interval range of {4.11, 14.47}.

  • From volatile.acidity vs citric.acid plot, we observe a negative correlation between them. Therefore I conclude that the wines that we can prefer containing a volatile.acidity of nearly 0.18 which would be of much taste, also containing the citric.acid of 1.7. some amount of outliers also exists in this plot.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

I have choosen this quality plot as it represents most of my finding in this analysis, most of the quality levels occur in 5th and 6th level and level 9 seems to be very low quality. quality seems to be the most important feature and property analyzing this data.

Plot Two

Description Two

This plot shows an relationship between quality and alcohol where we can observe that as alcohol percent increases in wine increases the quality of the wine. The reason i choosed this boxplot to observe higher alcohol percentage based on the quality. In this plot i have colored quality.factor which will represent all quality types with individual color.

plot Three

Description Three

From the above plot, we observe that quality 7 has the highest alcohol percentage and quality 5 has the lowest alcohol percentage. we have a correlation of -0.78 between density and alcohol. The reason i choosed this plot is to find the alcohol percentage based on the quality. I have used facet_wrap command to analyze density vs alcohol in each quality and also adjusted axis limit inorder to reduce overplotting.

Reflection

From the given white wine quality data set i have analyzed some the data with the help of some major variables. I have plotted necessary correlated plots of various variables.

  • Density will increase as alcohol percentage decreases.

  • volatile.acidity and citric.acid are negatively correlated where volatile.acidity depends on the taste of the wine where less amount of volatilegives the better taste and citric.acid depends on the addition of flavour and freshness to wine where higher the amount of citric acid increases the freshness and flavour to the wine.

  • free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide are positively correlated.

  • density and pH are negatively correlated.

  • alcohol and sulphates are negatively correlated.

  • In quality vs alcohol, quality 7 has the highest alcohol percentage and quality 5 has the lowest alcohol percentage. where they have a correlation of -0.78 between density and alcohol.

  • alcohol percent increases in wine also increases the quality of the wine in good quality type.

The intresting feature in analyzing is by finding the final plots with each plot with different type of plot such as boxplot and scatterplot. I have found and anlayzed different types of plot in univariate, Bivariate and Multivariate plots.

There is no much difficulty in analyzing the plots where it would be even more better if more properties of wine are included in the data set.

My future exploration from this data will be adding some other additional properties such as age of the wine, type of the wine etc. It would help us to analyze more information and create better models.
